      <div class="page-wrapper">
        <p class="lead">You said yes to being team mom — and suddenly you're in charge of a sports banquet. You're not alone. Thousands of parents do this every season, and most of them are figuring it out as they go. This guide is everything I wish someone handed me the first time.</p>

        <h2>Start with the Date — Everything Else Follows</h2>
        <p>The venue decides what you can do, and the date decides the venue. Before you plan anything else:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Talk to the coach</strong> — they know when stadiums, gyms, or school cafeterias are available</li>
          <li><strong>Check the school calendar</strong> — avoid prom, spring break, finals week, and other banquets</li>
          <li><strong>Book at least 6 weeks out</strong> — popular venues fill up fast, especially April through June</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Set a Realistic Budget</h2>
        <p>Most high school sports banquets cost between <strong>$15 and $35 per person</strong>. That includes food, venue, decorations, awards, and incidentals. Here's a rough breakdown for a team of 30 athletes plus families (roughly 80-100 people total):</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Venue:</strong> $0–500 (free if using school, $200–500 for a community hall)</li>
          <li><strong>Food:</strong> $1,200–$2,800 ($15–$35/person)</li>
          <li><strong>Decorations:</strong> $100–$300</li>
          <li><strong>Centerpieces:</strong> $50–$200</li>
          <li><strong>Awards/trophies:</strong> $50–$200</li>
          <li><strong>Programs/printouts:</strong> $20–$50</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Fundraising tip:</strong> Run a concession stand at one home game and earmark those profits for the banquet. One busy Friday night can cover most of your budget.</p>

        <h2>Build Your Team (You Don't Have to Do It Alone)</h2>
        <p>You need a small committee of 2-4 other parents. Divide and conquer:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Food coordinator</strong> — handles catering, dietary restrictions, cake, drinks</li>
          <li><strong>Decorations lead</strong> — centerpieces, tablecloths, banners, photo wall</li>
          <li><strong>Awards & program</strong> — works with coach on award categories, prints programs, sets up slideshow</li>
          <li><strong>Cleanup crew</strong> — 4 parents who stay 30 minutes after to pack up</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The 6-Week Countdown</h2>

        <h3>6 Weeks Out</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Book venue and send out save-the-date to families</li>
          <li>Pick your committee</li>
          <li>Decide on food (buffet is easiest — fewer staffing needs)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>4 Weeks Out</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Collect RSVPs and dietary restrictions</li>
          <li>Confirm food order with caterer</li>
          <li>Order centerpieces and decorations</li>
          <li>Ask coach for award categories and nominees</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2 Weeks Out</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Order trophies or plaques</li>
          <li>Build the photo slideshow (collect photos from parents)</li>
          <li>Print programs</li>
          <li>Reconfirm venue setup time</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>1 Week Out</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Assign seating chart</li>
          <li>Send reminder email with directions and timing</li>
          <li>Confirm who's arriving early to set up</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Decorations That Look Great Without Breaking the Bank</h2>
        <p>The biggest bang for your decoration buck comes from three things: tablecloths, centerpieces, and a photo wall. Everything else is optional.</p>

        <h3>Tablecloths</h3>
        <p>Buy or rent in team colors. Polyester tablecloths cost about $10-15 each and last for years. You can reuse them for every banquet.</p>

        <h3>Centerpieces</h3>
        <p>This is where a lot of team moms stress out, but it doesn't need to be complicated. You have two good options:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>DIY:</strong> Mason jars filled with team-color flowers, wrapped in ribbon. Cheap and pretty.</li>
          <li><strong>Custom sports-themed centerpieces:</strong> Pre-made 3D printed pieces shaped like footballs, basketballs, soccer balls — one per table. Athletes love them and they double as keepsakes.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="product-note">
