        <h3>Photo Wall</h3>
        <p>String lights across a wall. Clip action photos from the season to the string with clothespins. Add a team banner at the top. Cost: about $25. Result: the most photographed spot of the night.</p>

        <h2>One Week Before: The Team Mom Checklist</h2>
        <p>Print this. Check it twice.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>☐ Venue confirmed and keys/access arranged</li>
          <li>☐ Food order confirmed with final headcount</li>
          <li>☐ Allergies and dietary restrictions shared with caterer</li>
          <li>☐ Decorations gathered (tablecloths, centerpieces, banners)</li>
          <li>☐ Photo slideshow finished and tested on venue equipment</li>
          <li>☐ Awards/plaques labeled and organized by presentation order</li>
          <li>☐ Programs printed</li>
          <li>☐ Seating chart printed and table numbers ready</li>
          <li>☐ Emcee/speaker schedule confirmed with coach</li>
          <li>☐ Cleanup crew confirmed</li>
        </ul>

        <p>For a full printable checklist with timeline, budget template, and seating chart: <a href="/checklist/">Download the Complete Banquet Checklist →</a></p>

        <h2>Night-Of Tips from Veteran Team Moms</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Arrive 90 minutes early</strong> — you'll need every minute for setup</li>
          <li><strong>Bring an emergency kit</strong> — safety pins, tape, scissors, Sharpie, stain remover wipes, extra tablecloth</li>
          <li><strong>Assign someone to take photos</strong> — not you, you'll be running around</li>
          <li><strong>Hand off to the coach</strong> when the program starts — your job is done, enjoy the evening</li>
          <li><strong>Have a 10-minute cleanup plan</strong> — assign each committee member one task (pack centerpieces, strip tablecloths, gather trash)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>You've Got This</h2>
        <p>Planning a sports banquet is a lot of work, but it's also incredibly rewarding. When you see those athletes smiling, parents tearing up, and the coach looking proud — that's the moment it's all worth it. Every season, someone steps up to make it happen. This season, it's you.</p>

